1. Assess population structure

Lorenzo Bertola

Document last run on 2024-07-01

  • 0. Background
  • 0. Packages and data
  • 1. Filter by missingness
  • 2. PCOA all
  • 3. Re-assign population and remove hybrids
  • 4. PCOA by lineage
  • Genetic diversity by population

0. Background

I have now obtained a set of called genotypes for all individuals I plan to use for analyses of sex-determination. These individuals come from three lineages which meet at two contact zones. Some of these, from 2022, have never been analysed before and might contain mis-identified individuals and/or hybrids. I need to identify such individuals and remove them or assign them to the correct lineage. Additionally, I want to assess population structure so that I can designate population strata for analyses of sex-determination accordingly.

We can see that some of the samples that were IDentified as L. myola in the field (salmon colour) are actually from the northern lineage. Further, there is one F1 hybrid and 1 possible backcross hybrid. We are going to remove the hybrids, re-assign the LM samples to LN that belong to that lineage, and run gstacks separately on each lineage.

my.df <- as.data.frame(my.pcoa$scores)

my.df <- tibble::rownames_to_column(my.df, var = "IndName")

3. Re-assign population and remove hybrids

Now we will filter samples with a score between -30 and 0 on Axis 1 to remove the hybrids.

my.df <- my.df %>%
  filter(PC1 < -30 | PC1 > 0)

We will also filter the linkage mapping parents which have more than twice the coverage (they were filter at higher read depth) and often pop out as somewhat distinct (these are identified in the above plot with "Female" and "Male" in their name).

my.df <- my.df %>%
  filter(!str_detect(IndName, 'Female|Male'))

Now we are going to create one pop file per lineage

LN <- my.df %>%
  filter(PC1 < -30) %>%
  select(IndName) %>%
  add_column(Pop = "LN")

LM <- my.df %>%
  filter(PC1 > 0) %>%
  filter(str_detect(IndName, "LM_M")) %>%
  select(IndName) %>%
  add_column(Pop = "LM")

LS <- my.df %>%
  filter(PC1 > 0) %>%
  filter(str_detect(IndName, "LS_S")) %>%
  select(IndName) %>%
  add_column(Pop = "LS")

Let's save them as tab delimited files to be used for gstacks

write_delim(LS,
            file = "../2_PopStructure/2_popfile_LS",
            delim = "\t",
            col_names = FALSE)

write_delim(LN,
            file = "../2_PopStructure/2_popfile_LN",
            delim = "\t",
            col_names = FALSE)

write_delim(LM,
            file = "../2_PopStructure/2_popfile_LM",
            delim = "\t",
            col_names = FALSE)

Let's now run a pcoa for each lineage to assess how to subset populations for sex-linkage and gwas analyses. First we adjust the population assignment based on the previous pcoa plots

#make dataframe of individual names
my.names <- as.data.frame(my.gl@ind.names)
#name column to match the LM, LN, LS dataframes
colnames(my.names) <- "IndName"

#bind LM LN and LS
my.pops <- rbind(LM,LN,LS)

#join the ind names and the my.pops to add the adjusted population info
my.pops <- left_join(my.names,my.pops)
## Joining with `by = join_by(IndName)`
#change NA values to "NA"
my.pops <- my.pops %>% mutate(Pop = replace_na(Pop, "NA"))

#add "NA" to levels of populations to allow for hybrid individuals to have no population assigned, as we will exclude these
levels(my.gl@pop) <- c("LM","LN","LS","NA")

#set the new population
my.gl$pop <- as.factor(my.pops$Pop)

#clear environment
rm(my.pops,my.names)

Litoria serrata southern lineage (LS) shows 3-4 clusters. At the top we have YC, MR and DG samples (all from the Girramay-Kirrama region), on the bottom left we have two clusters, the top one with samples from Mungalli falls (MF) and Goolagan Creek (GC), and the bottom one with samples from Davies Creek (DV) and the 07 and 08 transects. On the right finally we have all the samples ffrom the southern end of the range, including No name creek 1 and 2 (N1, N2), Little Crystal Creek (LC), Ethel Creek (EC), Birthday Creek (BC) and Cloudy Creek (CL). These match what we knew about the species, and is well described in McKnight et al. (2019), who provided most of these samples.

Litoria serrata northern lineage shows two main clusters at this resolution, with samples north of the Daintree river (DO) being separated by the rest of the species. The left cluster on the other hand shows a north south trend, with the 07 and 08 transects being at the south edge of the species distribution, while the remaining samples are all found nearby the Kuranda region. Interestingly, there is temporal resolution as well, with the samples from the early 2000s (JC) appearing at the top, while the remaining samples collected between 2015 and 2022 sit in the middle.

Litoria myola shows the least structuring, which is to be expected given it is found in a 10x10 km region, compared to the other two lineages occurring over 100s of kilometers. Nevertheless, as documented before in Bertola et al. 2023 Con Gen, the eastern population appears somewhat distinct (JC). New samples from the east of the distribution (PL and BB), from two small peripheral populations never assessed before, fall within the JC cluster. Notably two samples (with 2 technical replicates each) cluster on their own on the top left. As we will see later these have lower call rate and possibly had poor quality extraction, so we will remove them.

my.df <- read_csv("../0_metadata/popIds.csv")

##  Column specification

pop(my.gl) <- my.names %>% pull(Pop5)
